## Class Name Utility (cn)

This module provides a utility function `cn` for conditionally combining CSS class names. It leverages `clsx` for efficient class name generation and `tailwind-merge` for de-duplicating and merging Tailwind CSS classes, ensuring a clean and optimized class attribute.

### Key Exports

*   `cn(...inputs: ClassValue[]): string`:
A function that takes a variable number of arguments (`ClassValue` which can be strings, arrays, or objects) and returns a single, merged string of CSS class names. It handles conditional class application and Tailwind CSS class conflicts gracefully.

### Usage Example

```typescript
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';

// Basic usage with static classes
const buttonClasses = cn('px-4', 'py-2', 'rounded-md');
// Result: 'px-4 py-2 rounded-md'

// Conditional classes
const isActive = true;
const dynamicClasses = cn('text-blue-500', isActive && 'font-bold', !isActive && 'text-gray-500');
// Result (if isActive is true): 'text-blue-500 font-bold'
// Result (if isActive is false): 'text-blue-500 text-gray-500'

// Merging Tailwind classes (tailwind-merge handles conflicts)
const mergedClasses = cn('hover:bg-blue-600', 'bg-blue-500', 'hover:bg-red-400');
// Result: 'bg-blue-500 hover:bg-red-400' (the last 'hover' class wins)

// Using with a React component
function MyButton({
  children,
  className,
  variant = 'primary'
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  className?: string;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}) {
  return (
    <button
      className={cn(
        'px-4 py-2 rounded-md font-semibold',
        variant === 'primary' && 'bg-blue-500 text-white hover:bg-blue-600',
        variant === 'secondary' && 'bg-gray-200 text-gray-800 hover:bg-gray-300',
        className // Allows passing custom classes
      )}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}
```
